Some say people are born to be leaders. For me the jury is out on that. I think leaders use their lived experience to learn what it is to be a leader.

Pete Buttigieg is a shining example of how public service helps shape leadership. There‚Äôs no better baptism of fire than being a mayor with all the challenges that brings.

The first time I heard him speak, I instinctively knew he was the type of politician that rarely graces the political stage. The more I researched the guy, the more impressed I was. He has served his country in uniform as well as in a suit, not something many if any MAGA Republicans can say.

His audacious run for President in 2020 was a measure of the man. Above all, it highlighted what an adept communicator he was. Take a listen to the clip below to see just how good he is. His ability to think on his feet and stay ad cool as a still pond regardless of the incoming, is truly impressive.

Joe Biden was not slow to notice just what value he could bring to his new government. How right he was. As Secretary of Transport, he has taken on the role intent to stamp his mark. As a skillful advocate for the societal benefits infrastructure, he‚Äôs able to articulate the administration‚Äôs position, not only on his brief, but on wider political challenges.

He‚Äôs a polyglot, who learns languages for fun, a musician and now a dad to twins with his husband Chasten. To be a great leader you have to understand the challenges of real American families and while it would be fair to say he didn‚Äôt grow up poor, you get the impression that equality and inclusion are both on his bingo card.

America you are blessed to have him. Be sure not to waste this gift.
